<b>Discriminative models</b> are a class of models used in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../488/233488.xml">
machine learning</link> for modeling the dependence of an unobserved variable <math>y</math> on an observed variable <math>x</math>. Within a statistical framework, this is done by modeling the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../458/504458.xml">
conditional probability distribution</link> <math>P(y|x)</math>, which can be used for predicting <math>y</math> from <math>x</math>. <p>

Discriminative models differ from <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../578/1222578.xml">
generative model</link>s in that they do not allow one to generate samples from the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../637/879637.xml">
joint distribution</link> of <math>x</math> and <math>y</math>.</p>
<p>

